---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
import PassRateBarChart from '../components/charts/PassRateBarChart';
import CostValueChart from '../components/charts/CostValueChart';
import RuntimeBarChart from '../components/charts/RuntimeBarChart';
import TokenUsageChart from '../components/charts/TokenUsageChart';
import QuadrantComparisonChart from '../components/charts/QuadrantComparisonChart';
import ModelSelector from '../components/charts/ModelSelector';
import BenchmarkHeatmap from '../components/charts/BenchmarkHeatmap';
---

<Layout title="Overview">
  <section class="mb-8">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="section-label"><span>About</span></div>
      <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-[var(--color-text-mid)] leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>
          <strong class="text-[var(--color-text)]">GitBench is a benchmark suite that evaluates how well language models perform on real-world Git tasks.</strong>
          Modern AI models claim coding prowess, but Git — the tool every developer uses daily — is a different kind of test.
          It requires procedural knowledge: knowing not just <em>what</em> to do, but <em>how</em> to express it as precise commands.
        </p>
        <p>
          Each model is tested across 204 fixtures — prompts that ask it to write commands like
          <code class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded">git log</code>,
          <code class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded">git rebase</code>, or
          <code class="font-mono text-[0.75rem] bg-[var(--color-surface)] px-1 py-0.5 rounded">git bisect</code>
          — and its output is compared against the expected command using a fuzzy similarity scorer.
          From basic log formatting to complex merge conflict resolution, every test runs in an isolated Git repository to ensure deterministic, reproducible results.
        </p>
        <p>
          Whether you're picking an AI coding assistant, evaluating your own fine-tuned model, or just curious how the latest
          LLMs handle Git, this dashboard gives you transparent, reproducible data — not marketing claims.
          The charts below show pass rates, costs, runtimes, and a detailed benchmark matrix across all evaluated models.
          <a href="/methodology" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] no-underline text-xs font-mono">Learn more about how GitBench works →</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="section-label">
      <span class="has-tooltip" data-tooltip="Percentage of 204 Git fixtures each model answered correctly. Higher bars = better Git skills.

80%+ = strong  |  50-80% = moderate  |  <50% = struggles" title="Pass rate — % of fixtures answered correctly. Higher is better.">Model Summary</span>
    </div>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-mid)] leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mb-4">
      Overall Git competency across all 204 fixtures. Higher bars mean the model answered more Git tasks correctly.
      Hover any bar for a breakdown by reasoning effort level.
    </p>
    <PassRateBarChart client:load />
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span class="has-tooltip" data-tooltip="Select any two metrics to compare model tradeoffs.

The shaded quadrant marks the direction where both criteria improve. Each point uses the best reasoning-effort variant for the selected pair." title="Quadrant comparison — compare two criteria and find the best combined tradeoff.">Quadrant Comparison</span>
    </div>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-mid)] leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mb-4">
      Pick two criteria to see where models land against both tradeoffs at once. The shaded quadrant is the optimal direction —
      for example, lower cost with higher pass rate, or lower token usage with lower cost.
    </p>
    <QuadrantComparisonChart client:load />
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span class="has-tooltip" data-tooltip="Total cost in USD to run all 204 fixtures through the model's API.

Only tracked for cloud models via OpenRouter. — means the model runs locally (Ollama) and has no API cost." title="Cost — total USD to evaluate all 204 fixtures via OpenRouter. — = local/Ollama.">Cost per Full Run</span>
    </div>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-mid)] leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mb-4">
      Total API cost (USD) to evaluate each model across all 204 fixtures. Models showing "—" run locally via Ollama and have no tracked cost.
      <a href="/methodology#cost-data" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] no-underline text-xs font-mono">Learn more →</a>
    </p>
    <CostValueChart client:load />
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span class="has-tooltip" data-tooltip="Total wall-clock time to complete all 204 fixture evaluations.

Affected by model speed, API latency, and rate limits. Not a pure speed benchmark." title="Runtime — wall-clock time for all 204 fixtures. Affected by API latency and rate limits.">Runtime (Wall Clock)</span>
    </div>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-mid)] leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mb-4">
      Total wall-clock time to run all 204 fixtures. This includes API latency and rate limiting overhead — it's not a pure model speed benchmark.
    </p>
    <RuntimeBarChart client:load />
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span class="has-tooltip" data-tooltip="Total tokens consumed across all 204 fixture evaluations.

Input tokens (prompts sent) + output tokens (responses generated). Less output for the same accuracy = more efficient." title="Token usage — total input + output tokens across all 204 fixtures.">Token Usage</span>
    </div>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-mid)] leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mb-4">
      Total tokens consumed (input + output) across all 204 fixtures. A rough measure of efficiency — delivering correct answers with fewer tokens is better.
    </p>
    <TokenUsageChart client:load />
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span class="has-tooltip" data-tooltip="Pass rate for each model on each Git skill category.

Rows = benchmarks (log, rebase, merge, etc.). Columns = models. Green cells = strong on that skill. Red = weak.

Click any cell to drill into fixture-level results." title="Benchmark matrix — pass rate per model per Git skill. Green = strong, red = weak.">Benchmark Matrix</span>
    </div>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-mid)] leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mb-4">
      The deep dive. Rows are Git task categories, columns are models. Green cells show where a model excels on a specific skill;
      red cells reveal its weaknesses. Look for patterns — some models dominate basics but struggle with complex workflows.
      <a href="/methodology#benchmark-design" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] no-underline text-xs font-mono">Learn more →</a>
    </p>
    <BenchmarkHeatmap client:load />
  </section>
</Layout>
